process of a transition between two German states, people have invented, and to some extent ritualized, cultural practices that both reflect and constitute profound identity transformations in a period of intense social discord. Where the World Ended combines a vivid ethnographic account of everyday life under socialist rule and after German reunification with an original investigation of the paradoxical human condition of a borderland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aBorderlandszGermany (East)vCase studies. 0aEthnologyzGermanyvCase studies. 0aSocial changezGermanyzKella. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aberlin wall.  aborder zones.  acontemporary.  acultural studies.  adaily life.  aeast germany.  aeconomic.  aeconomics.  aethnographic.  aethnography.  aeuropean history.  afinance.  agerman government.  agerman politics.  agovernment.  aidentity.  ainternational politics.  aliminal spaces.  aliminality.  amodern history.  amodern world.  apolitical.  apolitics.  ascholarly.  asocial studies.  asocialism.  asocialist.  atrue story.  awartime.  awest germany.  aworld history.  aworld politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092132040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520921320423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520921320/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles